{"id":"1708.01965","submitter":"Sourav Chatterjee","authors":"Sourav Chatterjee","title":"Rigidity of the three-dimensional hierarchical Coulomb gas","comments":"51 pages. To appear in Probab. Theory Related Fields","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A random set of points in Euclidean space is called `rigid' or `hyperuniform'\nif the number of points falling inside any given region has significantly\nsmaller fluctuations than the corresponding number for a set of i.i.d. random\npoints. This phenomenon has received considerable attention in recent years,\ndue to its appearance in random matrix theory, the theory of Coulomb gases and\nzeros of random analytic functions. However, most of the published results are\nin dimensions one and two. This paper gives the first proof of hyperuniformity\nin a Coulomb type system in dimension three, known as the hierarchical Coulomb\ngas. This is a simplified version of the actual 3D Coulomb gas. The interaction\npotential in this model, inspired by Dyson's hierarchical model of the Ising\nferromagnet, has a hierarchical structure and is locally an approximation of\nthe Coulomb potential. Hyperuniformity is proved at both macroscopic and\nmicroscopic scales, with upper and lower bounds for the order of fluctuations\nthat match up to logarithmic factors. The fluctuations have cube-root behavior,\nin agreement with a well-known prediction for the 3D Coulomb gas. For\ncompleteness, analogous results are also proved for the 2D hierarchical Coulomb\ngas and the 1D hierarchical log gas.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Aug 2017 02:19:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 22 Aug 2017 16:40:19 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 23 Aug 2017 20:37:29 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sun, 4 Mar 2018 04:35:26 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Thu, 28 Mar 2019 02:04:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-29"}
